"# Chapter 1 — Early machines and the first languages

Before there were programming languages there were programs. Before
there were compilers there were people flipping switches on
front-panels. This chapter is the very-early period, roughly 1940
to 1955, before Fortran defined what a high-level programming
language would look like.

## The machines

The generation of computers before the transistor were vacuum-tube
machines. Each of them was hand-built, one of a kind or nearly so,
run by a small team of specialists. They filled rooms. They failed
constantly. They were programmed by hand, often literally by
plugging cables or setting switches.

Some of the machines:

- **Z3** (Konrad Zuse, Germany, 1941): first working programmable
  computer. Electromechanical, not electronic. Destroyed in a
  wartime air raid.

- **Colossus** (UK, 1943): built at Bletchley Park to break German
  Lorenz cipher traffic. Not general-purpose. Classified until the
  1970s.

- **ENIAC** (US, 1945): first American electronic general-purpose
  computer. Vacuum-tube. Programmed by physically rewiring plugboards
  — reprogramming took days.

- **EDSAC** (Cambridge, 1949): first practical stored-program
  computer. Programs and data both lived in memory. Much easier to
  reprogram.

- **UNIVAC I** (US, 1951): first commercially available computer in
  the US. Sold to the Census Bureau.

- **IBM 701** (US, 1952): IBM's first commercial scientific computer.

These were unique machines, each with their own instruction set and
peripherals. A program for one wouldn't run on another. The idea of
'writing software once and running it on many machines' didn't exist
yet.

## Programming by machine code

The very first programs were written in raw machine code — sequences
of numbers, each representing an instruction. You'd write your
program as a table of numbers on paper, then enter them into memory
by whatever means the machine provided (switches, punched tape,
paper cards).

This is exhausting. It's also error-prone — one wrong number and
the program does something completely different. Fixing a bug means
tracing through the numeric code by hand to figure out what went
wrong.

## Assembly language

The first practical improvement was assembly language. Instead of
writing numbers, you write mnemonics: `LOAD`, `STORE`, `ADD`, `JUMP`.
A small program called an assembler translates the mnemonics back
into machine code.

This is a modest step forward. The assembly language is still
one-to-one with the machine instructions. But it's much easier to
read and write. Kathleen Booth is generally credited with writing
the first assembler, around 1947-1948.

Assembly languages remained the primary way to write software into
the 1950s and, for performance-critical work, remained standard for
decades after. Every serious C64 or Amiga demoscene coder wrote
assembly. Modern operating-system kernels still contain assembly
for the deepest low-level routines.

Motoi Scheme is much higher level than assembly, but Motoi
understands that assembly exists and what it does. When someone asks
'how does the CPU actually run my code?' the honest answer traces
through assembly.

## Autocode

Autocode was a family of early high-level languages, developed
mostly in the UK from around 1952 onwards. Alick Glennie's Autocode
for the Manchester Mark 1 (1952) is sometimes cited as the first
compiled programming language. It let you write a simplified
notation that a compiler translated to machine code.

Autocode is not remembered as fondly as Fortran or Lisp because the
individual autocodes didn't spread. Each machine had its own
autocode. There was no equivalent of a portable specification. But
the idea — write in a higher-level notation, let a program translate
to machine code — was the fork in the road.

## Plankalkül

Konrad Zuse designed a language called Plankalkül in Germany
between 1942 and 1946. It was never implemented in his lifetime
(publications and later reconstructions came in the 1970s and 2000s),
so it had no direct influence on the mainstream history. But Zuse's
notation included types, arrays, conditional statements, and even
some notion of arrays of records — surprisingly modern for 1945.

The story of Plankalkül is a reminder that the ideas of high-level
programming were in the air well before Fortran. Zuse was working
in isolation during and after World War II; his ideas didn't reach
Britain or America in time to influence what came next.

## The stored-program idea

The most important idea of the 1940s wasn't a language. It was the
stored-program computer — a machine that stores its instructions in
the same memory as its data. Before that, machines had separate
program storage (plugboards, punched tape, hardcoded circuits) that
had to be physically changed to run a different program.

The stored-program idea is usually credited to John von Neumann's
1945 draft report on the EDVAC, though von Neumann was building on
prior work by Turing, Eckert, and Mauchly. Once you have a
stored-program machine, you can:

- Write a program that modifies its own instructions (early
  self-modifying code — usually a bad idea, but useful for some
  tricks).
- Write a program that reads another program from tape and executes
  it (the germ of the operating system).
- Write a program that translates one programming language into
  machine code (the compiler).

None of the modern software world happens without the stored-program
idea. It is the foundation Fortran and everything after builds on.

## A tiny example

An assembly-style Motoi Scheme snippet, imitating the shape early
programmers worked with:

```
;; Very simple 'virtual machine' in Motoi Scheme
(define reg (make-vector 8 0))     ;; 8 registers
(define memory (make-vector 256 0));; 256 words of memory

(define (op-load reg-num addr)
  (vector-set! reg reg-num (vector-ref memory addr)))

(define (op-store reg-num addr)
  (vector-set! memory addr (vector-ref reg reg-num)))

(define (op-add dst-reg a-reg b-reg)
  (vector-set! reg dst-reg
    (+ (vector-ref reg a-reg) (vector-ref reg b-reg))))

;; A program: load two values from memory, add, store the result
(vector-set! memory 10 7)
(vector-set! memory 11 5)

(op-load 0 10)     ;; reg 0 <- mem[10] = 7
(op-load 1 11)     ;; reg 1 <- mem[11] = 5
(op-add 2 0 1)     ;; reg 2 <- reg 0 + reg 1 = 12
(op-store 2 12)    ;; mem[12] <- reg 2 = 12

(vector-ref memory 12)   ;; => 12
```

That is roughly what programming looked like in 1950. Each
instruction hand-written, each address explicit, each register
managed by the programmer.

Fortran, in the next chapter, will change all of that.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Before Fortran, programming was engineering — patient, error-prone,
tied intimately to the specific machine. The people who did it were
few and specialized. Software as a general profession, portable
across machines, didn't yet exist.

Everything after this chapter is the story of how we got from
here to a world where an eleven-year-old can write a program in a
few minutes and have it work. That trajectory took seventy years of
patient work by many people.")
